Liquidated damages are monetary sums stipulated in a contract that the contractor must pay to the owner if they fail to achieve specific performance conditions, such as finishing the project on time or within budget. They are often included in building contracts to encourage the contractor to adhere to the agreed-upon timeline and budget. Liquidated damages are crucial in building projects for a variety of reasons, including: They provide a financial incentive to the contractor to complete the job on time: Liquidated damages incentivize the contractor to finish the job on schedule by providing a monetary penalty for delays. They give monetary remuneration to the owner: If the contractor fails to meet the deadline, liquidated damages allow the owner to be paid for any extra expenditures or lost income as a consequence of the delay. They give a straightforward and objective measure of delay: Liquidated damages give a clear and objective measure of delay that may be used to establish the amount of damages to be paid in the case of a disagreement. They may assist to reduce risk: Both parties may better forecast and prepare for the possible financial effect of delays by incorporating liquidated damages in the contract. It is vital to highlight that liquidated damages should be considered a realistic estimate of the actual losses that the owner would experience as a result of the delay rather than a punishment. Furthermore, liquidated damages should be properly specified and mentioned in the contract, and both parties should evaluate and agree on them before signing the contract. 